This paper deals with the problem of coordinated beamforming in wireless cellular systems, which is a topic that falls under the intersection of several sub-fields in computer science. The paper specifically focuses on the impact of channel state information (CSI) errors on the performance of coordinated beamforming, which is a problem that is typically studied in the context of information theory (cs.IT) and wireless networking (cs.NI). The paper also proposes a worst-case robust design formulation that involves optimizing the transmission power of base stations subject to signal-to-interference-plus-noise ratio (SINR) constraints, which is a problem that is relevant to control systems (cs.SY) and machine learning (cs.LG). Finally, the paper presents simulation results to evaluate the performance of the proposed approach, which is a topic that falls under the category of multimedia (cs.MM) since it involves analyzing the quality of wireless transmissions.
